March 29, 2012 12:00 p.m. 

Sam Valenti III: A brilliant, memorable, larger-than-life character
              A lifetime of achievement earns M&A
  award  


 




									Tom Henderson								


Facebook 

linkedin 

Twitter 

RSS Feed 




									Staff Blog								
																						: Venture capital, banking, private equity, tech startups													




TwitterFacebookLinkedInGoogle+CommentsEmailPrinter-friendly version 


Finance









 




Sam Valenti III
 


I've been at Crain's for nearly seven years, now. The most memorable person I've met on the job here? Hands down, it's Sam Valenti III, who was profiled in Monday's print edition as the winner of the lifetime achievement award for the upcoming annual Crain's M&A Awards.
I've been covering venture capital since the late 1980s, when I was a free-lancer and realized VC was a niche no one else in town was writing about and might be a source of recurring income.
When Crain's offered me the finance beat in 2005, I took it with the intention of doing more with VC than Crain's had traditionally done. The timing was perfect — the economy was booming, more VC firms were opening their doors, and the state, through the $109 million 21st Century Fund and the $95 million Michigan Venture Fund, was about to make a lot more money available for local funds to invest with.
Late 2006, early 2007, I was on the phone with Lindsay Aspegren, a friend and old source at North Coast Technology Investors LP in Ann Arbor. He mentioned someone named Sam Valenti.
"Who's Sam Valenti?" I asked.
"How can you cover venture capital in this town and not know Sam Valenti?" he said.
"I don't know. Who is he?"
"Sam Valenti is the godfather of venture capital here," said Aspegren. "I'm going to give you his cell, and you call him and go meet him. I'll call him first and tell him I told you to call him. Give me five minutes and then call him."
"Yes, sir."
Five minutes later, I called Sam.
He was, he said quietly, an old Sicilian. Been at this a long time. Had a little shop in Blooomfield Hills. Ran some money for old family friends. Had avoided publicity over the years but was at a point in his life where he wouldn't mind saying what was on his mind. So, come on out.
We agreed on a time and, more out of loyalty to Lindsay than anything else, I drove out. Not that I didn't mind an excuse to get out of the office or the chance to add another source to the Rolodex, but I wasn't expecting much.
Valenti had planted a vision in my mind of a small, wizened old Sicilian, maybe a financial stud back in the day but past his prime, a little office, managing a few bucks for old friends who were happy to throw him a bone in his dotage.
So, I drove out Woodward to Bloomfield Hills, pulled into the parking lot of a large office building, walked in the front door and saw an office off the lobby that proclaimed Valenti Capital.
I walked in and was struck by the mahogany, the artwork, the sense of real money. The receptionist made a call to Sam, who told her to send me back. She pointed out the hallway to the right and told me to head down it.



 


 
Lindsay Aspegren
 


It was a hall that seemed to stretch to infinity. On the way down I walked past some stadium seating on the left — some 20-25 seats, now empty, aimed at a bank of TV screens to the right, now off.
I looked back at the end of the hall just as Sam walked out of his office at the far end and started striding toward me. Little, wizened? Has anyone ever had a worse misconception?
Valenti is about 6-2, looks like a million bucks in his tailored suit and crisp white shirt, walks with his shoulders back and head erect, with a cock-of-the-walk stride. Was in his early 60s, then, looked 15 years younger.
Maybe you've heard of my son, he said. That being Sam Valenti IV. I had. He'd been one of our 20s in their 20s and, unlike his father, showed up frequently in our electronic archives. His dad had rarely appeared, even though he'd been head of the investment committee for the state of Michigan pension fund for many years and had been president of Masco Capital, the pension and investment arm of Masco Corp.
I would find out over time, mostly from others, that Sam had singlehandedly created the concept of venture capital and private equity as an investment class for institutional investors in Michigan.
With money from Masco, and often matching money from the state pension fund, the state's VC and private equity communities were born and grew.
Everyone was rewarded. Masco made money, the VC and PE firms made money, and the state's pension fund grew from about $5 billion to about $52 billion on Valenti's watch.
He'd decided to meet with me, he explained, because he figured he was at a point in his life where he wouldn't mind commenting on the issues of the day or serving as a source. Until now, he said, he figured his job was serving Masco and Richard Manoogian, its president and CEO, and had scrupulously avoided the press.
And he's been a good source ever since. He tipped me to the Renaissance Venture Capital Fund he was trying to raise, he's helped clarify and put into context various issues of the day, and he's explained the various ups and downs of the market over the years.
In the dark days of the recession, when a Great Depression seemed to be looming, my young multimedia colleague, Nate Skid, and I went and sat at Sam's knee for an hour while he gave a history lesson on how the economy had got to that point.
Without notes, and without pause, speaking in complete sentences and paragraphs and with none of the verbal ticks most of us need, Sam wove in various threads from around the world the last three decades and tied them into a bow. Nate posted the entire lecture, a tour de force, on our Web site. I pulled out excerpts for the print edition. It was a remarkable tour de force and proof, not that any was needed, of Sam's intellect.
Raj Kothari, a managing director at Birmingham-based Seneca Partners, a VC firm and investment bank, worked for Masco Capital for six years. He called after reading the story on Sam's lifetime-achievement award to pass on some thoughts.
"Sam is a great guy to work for. I had so much fun and learned so much. I was doing things at 22 I never should have been entrusted with. He really is a great guy and a legendary character," he said.
Gerry Boylan, managing director at Royal Oak-based Long Point Capital, a private equity company, passed on some thoughts in an email: "Great choice on Sam Valenti for your upcoming awards. He's one of the most interesting people I've ever worked with or, for that matter, ever met."
The M&A awards, in conjunction with the local chapter of the Association for Corporate Growth, are on April 19 at the Somerset Inn in Troy. Valenti, who prides himself on his public speaking, says he's planning on bringing down the house with his speech that night. 
